         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne ¶ 29/9/77. ¶  ¶ You were quite right, dear Mr Bailey, in referring your little Orchid to Bolbophyll. ¶  lichenastrum. It is a much larger form than the one I described; its leaves are twice ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">77.09.29</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Frederick Bailey</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">ML MSS B202, Mitchell Library, State Library of New South Wales, Sydney</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">29/9/77.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>You were quite right, dear Mr Bailey, in referring your little Orchid to Bolbophyll.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>Bolbophyllum.</p>
               </note> lichenastrum. It is a much larger form than the one I described; its leaves are twice or thrice longer. Your thoughtful notes enable me to complete the description.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Original description based on Dallachy's specimen (MEL 544728) in B69.10.01, p. 60; the additional description using Bailey's specimen is in 'Additamenta', B77.13.08, p. 119.</p>
               </note> Dallachys plant from Rocks,<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Dallachy's label with MEL 544728, collected at Seaview Range near Rockingham Bay, <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>notes that it was 'so firmly attached to the stones or rocks that I could hardly get it off'.</p>
               </note> according to his specimens had the leaves so closely set, as to resemble a lichenlike crust.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In the number of the Fragm., now in print, I described your Atherosperma as A repandulum.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B77.10.02, p. 105, based on MEL 3181 (Dallachy collection, 10 May 1868) and MEL 3182 (Bailey collection, 1877).</p>
               </note> I had it also from Dallachy and named it 10 years ago, but have waited with publishing the species until I saw more specimens. It is very near A. micranthum, but, so far as I can judge from the material before me, it seems really distinct</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Please give the enclosed introduction-letter to Dr Bancroft.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Letter not found. Dr Joseph Bancroft visited Europe in 1877-8 and while there discussed his work on Pituri and provided specimens for analysis (Bancroft (1879), p. 3).</p>
               </note> Let the Doctor take to Berlin a living plant of the <name key="Helmholtzia">Helmholtzia</name>.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M had erected the genus <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Helmholtzia">Helmholtzia</name>
                     </seg> (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">H. acorifolia</seg>), based on Dallachy's specimen collected on 16 November 1868 (MEL 3439), in honour of the Berlin physicist and physiologist Hermann (von) Helmholtz in B66.12.04, pp. 202-3. See also J. Dallachy to M, 26 January 1870 (in this edition as 70-01-26a).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Atherosperma%20micranthum">Atherosperma micranthum</name>
            </p>
